turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Good God.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Do you think it's them?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I wonder.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Nobody knows we're here except Freda and she wouldn't ring up.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: It must be them then.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Well what are we going to do?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: We'll be alright, darling.  Whatever happens, aren't we?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Now and always sweet.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I don't care then.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: It was bound to come sooner or later.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Hello.  Hello.  What?  Wrong number.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Ahh.  It sent shivers up my spine.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: What shall we do if they suddenly walk in on us?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Behave exquisitely.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: With the most perfect poise.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Certainly I shall probably do a court curtsy.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Things that ought to matter dreadfully don't matter at all when one's happy, do they?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: What is so horrible is that one can't stay happy.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Don't say that, my darling.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: It's true the whole business is very poor joke.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Meaning that sacred and beautiful thing love.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Yes, meaning just that.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: What does it all mean?  That's what I asked myself in my ceaseless quest for ultimate truth.  Dear God what does it all mean?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Don't laugh at me.  I'm serious.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: You mustn't be serious, my darling.  It's just what they want.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Who's they?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: All the futile moralists who try to make life unbearable.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Laugh at them, be flippant, laugh at everything, all their sacred shibboleths

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: flippancy brings out the acid in their damn sweetness and light.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: If I must laugh at everything, I must laugh at us too.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Certainly you must.  We are figures of fun alright.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Oh, how long will it last, this ludicrous, over-bearing love of ours?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Well who knows?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: We always want to bicker and fight.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: No that fire will fade long with our passion.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Oh, dear shall we like that?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: It all depends on how well we've played.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: What happens if one of us dies?  Does the one that's left still laugh?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Yes.  Yes.  with all his might.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Well that's serious enough, isn't it?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: No, no it isn't.  Death is very laughable such a cunning little mystery.  All done with mirrors.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Darling, I believe you're talking nonsense.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: So is everyone else in the long run.  Let's be superficial and pity the poor philosophers.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Let's blow trumpets and squeakers and enjoy the party as much as we can like small quite idiotic little school children.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Let's savor the delight of the moment.  Come and kiss me darling before your body rots and worms pop in and out of your eye sockets.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Elliott, worms don't pop.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I don't mind what you do, see. you can paint yourself green all over

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: and dance naked in the place Place Vendome and rush away with all the men in the world and I shan't say a word as long as you love me best.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Thank you, dear.  The same applies to you except that if I catch you so much as looking at another woman, I'll kill you.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Do you remember that awful scene in Venice?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Which particular one?

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: The one where you bought that little painted wooden snake and put it on my bed.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Oh, Charles.  That was his name.  Charles he did wriggle so beautifully.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Horrible thing.  I hated it.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Yes, I know you did.  You threw him out of the window into the Grand Canal.  I don't think I'll ever forgive you for that.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: How long did that row last?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: It went on intermittently for days.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: The worst one was in Cannes when your curling irons burnt holes in my dressing gown.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: It burnt my comb too and all the towels in the bathroom.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: Ah, we were much younger then.  That was a rouser wasn't it?

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: That was the first time you ever hit me.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: You didn't hit me- I didn't hit you very hard.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: Then the manager came in and found us rolling about on the floor biting and scratching like panthers.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: I shall never forget his face.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: How ridiculous.  How utterly, utterly ridiculous.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: We were very much younger then.

turns.speaker: F
turns.content: And very much sillier.

turns.speaker: M
turns.content: As a matter of fact, the real cause of that row was Peter Burden.
